Date: Wed 17 Oct 2001 2:58 PM
From: <EdRegis@aol.com> [edited]

I've been following all the [bioterrorism] hysteria [reports] on
ProMED-mail. For a discussion of how we might help to simmer down the
ongoing hysteria here in the US, might I offer that in an attempt to place
these risks in perspective someone should put out comparative disease
incidence for diseases other than anthrax as communicated by letter.
I have seen a reference to foodborne disease incidence annual in the US as
76 million cases annually, with 315 000 hospitalizations and 5000
deaths. Also, about 100 people in the US are killed annually by
"lightning, lightning shock, stroke, or thunderbolt." An average of 300
people annually in the US die by "drowning, submersion in bathtub." And in
1991, 1247 people died by "inhalation or ingestion of food." (These latter
from CDC's National Center for Health Statistics.)
In other words, you are far more likely to die by taking a bath or eating
your dinner than by opening an anthrax-laced envelope.
---
Ed Regis
<EdRegis@aol.com>
