Date: 12 Oct 2001 15:26:01 -0500
From: David Freedman <dfreedman@GEOMED.DOM.UAB.EDU> [edited]

The CDC and other authorities I think were put in a difficult situation in
making the recommendations for PEP [post-exposure prophylaxis] for _B.
anthracis_ in Florida. Drug sensitivities were not known at the time.
Clinical judgement is always needed to manage individual patients, yet
recommendations need to be made in a broad general public health context.
There are no human clinical data for prophylaxis.
My understanding is that most of the authoritative recommendations out
there are being based on the high-level Consensus Statement on Anthrax as a
Biological Weapon published in JAMA 1999;281:1735-45:
<http://jama.ama-assn.org/issues/v281n18/fpdf/jst80027.pdf>
In Table 3 Cipro[floxacin] is recommended as Initial Therapy (prophylaxis)
of choice
when sensitivities are unknown. Then Optimal Therapy if Strain is Proven
Susceptible is a choice of Amoxi[cillin] or Doxy[cycline] for 60d. The
choice of drugs for
Pregnancy and Children follow the same considerations except that
Doxy[cycline] is
not recommended at all in either case. A footnote adds that in vitro data
indicate that ofloxacin 400 q12h or levofloxacin 500 q24 can be
substituted. [The latter are fluoroquinolones similar to ciprofloxacin in
structure and mechanism of action. These recommendations may speak to
potential problems with adequacy of supplies of ciprofloxacin that have
been raised by the news media. - Mod.ES]
--
D. Freedman
<dfreedman@GEOMED.DOM.UAB.EDU>
