Date: Wed 17 Oct 2001 12:40 PM
From: Sarena Seifer <sarena@u.washington.edu> [edited]

Anthrax: What Every Clinician Should Know
Live Broadcast: 18 Oct 2001, 4:00 - 5:30 PM EDT
This live satellite and web broadcast will present clinical guidelines and
procedures for the early recognition, diagnosis, treatment, and reporting
of anthrax exposure. A panel of experts from the CDC will provide an
overview of clinical, laboratory, and public health preparedness for
potential _Bacillus anthracis_ incidence. A toll-free audio line is also
available for those unable to arrange a viewing location. Sponsored by the
American Hospital Assn., American Medical Assn., Public Health Training
Network, CDC, and the University of North Carolina School of Public Health.
For full details including satellite technical specifications and
fax/call-in numbers for Q&A during the program, refer to the Acrobat Reader
(PDF) flyer at
<http://www.phf.org/anthrax.pdf>
Information in HTML is posted at
<http://www.phf.org/anthraxHTML.htm>
A link to the web cast will be provided on the day of the broadcast at:
<http://www.cdc.gov/phtn>
CDC PUBLIC HEALTH EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESS & RESPONSE
<http://www.bt.cdc.gov/>
Contains bioterrorism fact sheets, guidelines, notification protocols,
news, Frequently Asked Questions, links, and more. Includes information
about CDC roles and national programs such as the National Pharmaceutical
Stockpile and the Health Alert Network.
--
Sarena Seifer
<sarena@u.washington.edu>
[I have received a series of messages concerning the probability of finding
_B.anthracis_ spores in random nasal swabs or seropositive individuals in a
large random survey. It would be extraordinary to find anything except
false positives unless one included workers in wool mills or bone meal
plants, and particularly when they handled imported wool and bones, or
farm/ranch workers in Texas, Nevada, or the upper Mid-West, where we still
see livestock cases.
Domestically the pathogen is limited to very few areas, and I have yet to
find a clinical veterinarian from these places who has ever been
vaccinated. Our colleague Jack Woodall suggested that anthrax might be
found in veterinary schools/colleges, but frankly they don't see cases
except by accident, as in Oklahoma a few years ago, when an "interesting"
dead sheep was brought into the college's necropsy facility.
The director of my own laboratory swabs the lab down herself with 5%
Chlorox each Friday and after any procedure. We offer visiting scientists
swabs and blood agar plates and make the offer of a free dinner anywhere in
town if (s)he finds any viable organisms. We haven't had to do that for
some years now. I cannot speak for others' laboratories. - Mod.MHJ]
